		<tr valign=top>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				&quot;Altough you might be getting a Motherboard with the latest chipset, its a crap board which does not have any features like USB and I do not think you can exchange ECC ram for regular 3200+ ram&quot; <br>  <br> The board has connections for serial hard drives, USB 2.0, firewire and an 8x AGP slot. You can use either ECC or non ECC ram. Since this system is sold as a server it has to be rock solid, so the motherboard is very stable. I've left the thing running for a month, never shutting it off and it's still going strong. <br> My main gaming rig uses an Asus P4C800-E board, which is the Intel 875 chipset. The Dell board has all the same features and the same exact board layout. Aside from some color differences the two boards are identical. <br>  <br> &quot;Also I went there and priced one out and It came to a whopping $1000 without any software, no video card, a shitty Mo-Bo no R-W DVD or CD rom.....&quot; <br>  <br> I got mine for $247. Just add ram and a video card and you're set. You can do it for $500. I know because I have the poweredge server from Dell. <br>  <br> &quot;Add all these components to the system and your still looking at a $1500+ system.&quot; <br>  <br> No, you're looking at a decent gaming system for $500, which is his budget. With a higher budget then I would whole heartedly reccomend building your own. But he does not have a higher budget. 
