		<tr valign=top>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				You could possibly build a good gaming PC for around $600, but you would have to shop smart. I am lucky to have a store in my city that has great prices on componets, I actually found them on Pricewatch where they were the 3rd lowest vendor on one item. I have to pay tax, but no shipping so it evens out. <br>  <br> For example, I got a combination of AthlonXP 2700+ and A7N8X motherboard for about $220. Geforce 4 ti 4800 video card, 8x AGP and 128 ram for $120. 80 Gig Western Digital HDD for $80. ATX Case with 420watt PS for $55. Add in CD-RW and misc other items and I got everything for less than $600 w/ tax. <br>  <br> As for the OS, they sell OEM version of XP Pro (full, not upgrade) for about $120. <br>  <br> I still agree that for most people it makes more sense to get a complete PC, it saves a lot of time and hassle, plus it's becoming more common for big name vendors to sell gaming PCs.
