			<td class="BoardRowA" colspan=2 width="83%"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Date Posted:</span> 
			2/29 7:36am 
			<span style="font-weight: bold;">Subject:</span> RE: Building a computer			
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr valign=top>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				You will not build a good gaming PC for that kind of money. <br>  <br> Here are some tips anyway: <br>  <br> Generally today's processors are available in a *range* of 3-4 different speeds at a time. Buy the lowest that is available. For example a 2.6 instead of a 3.4 GHz. The fact is, processor speed is not the limiting factor in your system, storage access is. <br>  <br> Video cards... these days you can get a good card that is not top of the line. It will still cost you though, Look at NVidia or ATI chipsets one or two steps below the top of the line. Currently the ATI Radeon 9800xt is the king of the hill; barely beating out the best NVidia One will run you about 400 USD though. <br>  <br> Any decent MB with the newer intel chipsets has sound on board. That is good enough for me. I have a home theater, I am not going to use my PC as one. <br>  <br> Stay away from LCD monitors. Very few of them are good for gaming. Also the technology is not improving much and new technology is coming (OLED). If you have rooom on your desk a CRT is a MUCH better investment. You will get MUCH more performance for much less price.  <br>  <br> 1GB of ram. Ram is relatively cheap so do it. <br>  <br> Win2K, not XP <br>  <br> Salvage everything else. <br>  <br> Finally, <br>  <br> Keep your machine as clean as humanly possible. That means NO antivirus software. Just don't keep anything you can't afford to lose on your harddrive. CD-RW drives and cd's are dirt cheap. Use them to back up valuable stuff. <br>   <br> Every 3 months or so, wipe out everything and reinstall. <br>  <br> Those last two things will improve your system performance as much as anything else. <br> 		

			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr align="right"valign="bottom">
			<td colspan=2 class="BoardRowB">
				
					<a class="BoardRowBLink" 
					href="/post.asp?brd=5001&topic=64872410">Post Reply</a>  
